description._value: In this study, GC/LC-MS-based metabolomic analyses in conjuction with multivariate statistics were applied to investigate the effect of exogenous MeJA on the metabolome of Centella asiatica cells. C. asiatica is an important medicinal plant with a wide range of bioactivities associated with its secondary metabolites. Concentration-dependent changes in the metabolite profiles, indicative of the cellular response to MeJA, were observed. Annotated metabolites included a range of sesquiterpenoids that illustrates the stimulatory effect of MeJA on terpenoid pathways. In contrast, flavanoids were mostly negatively correlated with the treatment. The presence of the five bioactive cyclic sesquiterpenoids in MeJA-elicited cells and other annotated metabolites (abscisic acid, fatty acids, phytosterols and metabolites of shikimate-phenylpropanoid pathways) indicates that the changes in the metabolome are associated with a defensive function in response to elicitation by MeJA, rather than just the amplication of existing terpene pathways. These results provided a detailed and comprehensive picture of metabolic changes occurring in C. asiatica cells in response to MeJA elicitation and contribute to the understanding of flexible and controllable aspects of metabolic manipulation

Two extraction methods were used: a selective extraction (chloroform extracts) to target non-polar metabolites and a general methanol extraction for mid-polar and polar compounds. Chloroform extracts were prepared as previously described, using the dispersive liquid-liquid microextraction (DLLME) method (Tugizimana et al. 2012). Briefly, 24 h post treatment, the excess media was filtered using a Buchner funnel and the cells were collected. Two grams of cells were re-suspended in 20 mL of methanol and homogenised using an Ultra Turrax homogenizer. The homogenates were centrifuged at 5525 × g for 7 min at 25 °C. The supernatants were placed into 50 mL round-bottom flasks, and the methanol evaporated to 1 mL at 50 °C using a Buchi Rotavapor R-200. To this, 1 mL of the crude aqueous extract, 200 µL of chloroform and 100 µL of methanol were added.  The mixture was vortexed for 30 s and centrifuged at 15 000 × g for 6 min at 25 °C in a glass centrifuge tube. Using a syringe, the bottom chloroform extraction layer was removed and filtered through 0.22 µm nylon filters, and placed into pre-labelled GC glass vials containing glass inserts and fitted with slitted caps. A general methanol extraction was carried out as previously described, with modification where necessary (Madala et al. 2014; Tugizimana et al. 2014). The resulting 50% methanol extracts were filtered through 0.22 μm filters and placed into pre-labelled UHPLC glass vials fitted with inserts and slitted caps.

GC-MS = A 1 µl aliquot of chloroform sample was injected into the GC-MS instrument in splitless mode and the injection temperature of 250 °C. The overall programmed-temperature GC run included zones with different temperature gradient (multi-linear programming) with initial and final isothermal zones. The initial GC oven temperature was 40 °C for 4 min, increased by 25 °C min-1 to 240 °C, then increased to 300 °C at a rate of 5 °C min-1 and held at 300 °C for 5.00 min

LC-MS = A binary solvent mixture was used consisting of water (eluent A) containing 10 mM formic acid (pH 2.3) and acetonitrile (Romil Pure Chemistry, Cambridge, UK) (eluent B). The initial conditions were 95% A at a flow rate of 0.4 mL min-1 and were kept constant for 2 min. A gradient was introduced to change the chromatographic conditions to 5% A at 22 min. The conditions were kept constant for 3 min to flush the analytical column where after the column was returned to initial conditions at 27 min and allowed to equilibrate for 3 min. The run time was 30 min and the injection volume was 5 µl

GC-MS = The MS was operated using EI at 70 eV. Helium was used as the carrier gas, and the column flow rate set at 1 mL min-1. The ion source temperature was set at 200 °C, and the detector voltage was set at 0.5 kV to prevent the oversaturation of the detector. The solvent cut time for the MS was set at 5 min and EI scan mode was used for identification covering the range of 50-500 m/z. 


LC-MS = The SYNAPT G1 mass spectrometer was used in V-optics and operated in electrospray ionisation (ESI) mode to detect the compounds of interest. Leucine enkephalin (50 pg mL-1) was used as reference calibrant to obtain typical mass accuracies between 1 and 3 mDa. The mass spectrometer was operated in both positive and negative mode with a capillary voltage of 2.5 kV, the sampling cone at 17 V and the extraction cone at 4 V. The scan time was 0.1 s covering the 100 to 1000 Da mass range. The source temperature was 120°C and the desolvation temperature was set at 450 °C. Nitrogen gas was used as the nebulisation gas at a flow rate of 800 L h-1. The software used to control the hyphenated system and perform all data manipulation was MassLynx 4.1 (SCN 704, Waters Corporation, Milford, MA, USA).

The raw data was processed using the software specific to the analytical platform used. For GC-MS data, the Profiling Solution software (Shimadzu, Kyoto, Japan) was used for data processing. The parameters were default settings except for the following: 6 – 25 min retention time (Rt) range of the chromatogram, ion m/z tolerance of 500 mDa, ion Rt tolerance of 0.5 min and ion intensity threshold of 1000 counts. The timebase ‘Warping’ method was used for the chromatogram alignment. For LC-MS data, ESI positive and negative raw data were extracted using MassLynxTM XS software and analysed with MarkerLynxTM software (Waters Corporation, Mildford, MA, USA). The MarkerLynx software extracts the raw LC-MS data and produces a matrix of Rt-m/z variable pairs, with the m/z peak intensity for each sample. Software parameters were set to analyse the 2-26 min Rt range of the chromatogram, mass range 100-700 Da, mass tolerance 0.01 Da, mass window 0.05 Da and a Rt window of 0.20 min. The data matrices obtained from Profiling Solution (GC-MS data) and MarkerLynx (LC-MS) processing were exported to SIMCA 13.0 software (Umetrics, Umea, Sweden) for principal component analysis (PCA) and orthogonal projection to latent structures-discriminant analysis / orthogonal partial least squares-discriminant analysis (OPLS-DA).

XCMS analyses of LC-MS data = Following the upload of the raw data files (netCDF), parameters for XCMS processing were as follows: centWave for feature detection (with 15 ppm as a maximal tolerated m/z deviation in consecutive scans, minimum chromatographic peak width of 5 s and maximum peak width of 20 s); obwarp method for retention time correction (profStep = 1, step size to use for profile generation). The chromatogram alignment parameters included: minfrac of 0.5 (minimum fraction of samples necessary in at least one of the sample groups for it to be a valid group), bw of 5 s (allowable retention time deviations) and mzwid of 0.015 (width of overlapping m/z slices to use for peak density chromatograms and grouping peaks across samples). The relative quantification of metabolite features was based on EIC (extracted ion chromatogram) areas, and statistical test was performed using unpaired parametric t-test (Welch t-test) method, with p-value and fold change thresholds of 0.01 and 1.5 respectively for highly significant features and p-value threshold of 0.05 for significant features.

The selected mass ions from the SIMCA-derived S- and Variable Importance in Projection (VIP) plots were putatively annotated according to the Metabolomic Standards Initiative, level 2 (Sumner et al. 2007). For the LC-MS platform, selected mass ions obtained from MarkerLynx data were putatively identified using the Taverna workbench (www.taverna.org.uk) for PUTMEDID_LCMS metabolite identification workflows. The Taverna workflows allow for integrated, automated and high-throughput annotation and putative metabolite identification from LC-ESI-MS metabolomic data. The workflows consist of correlation analysis, metabolic feature annotation and metabolite annotation (Brown et al. 2011). For the GC-EI-MS platform, the respective mass spectra of the extracted ion peaks of the selected mass ions from S- and VIP plots were searched against the NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology) and Wiley mass spectra libraries (2007 versions) for similarity matches. This spectral comparison provided putative empirical formulae and structures, which were further searched in databases such as the Dictionary of Natural Products (www.dnp.chemnetbase.com) and ChemSpider (www.chemspider.com). The library search results were evaluated based on the probability factor, a match factor provided by the search algorithms that describes how unique a spectrum is, compared to all other spectra in the library (Kanani and Klapa 2007; Kanani et al. 2008). Only spectra with probability hits in the range from 650 to 900 or above, were considered.

The statistically selected features in XCMS analyses are automatically annotated by searching the METLIN metabolite database, producing thus a list of putative identities based on accurate mass measurements. In this study, the XCMS online annotation parameters were set as follows: isotopes and adducts search, m/z absolute error of 0, ppm error of 5 and the tolerance for database search of 10 ppm.

title._value: Metabolomics-derived insights into the manipulation of terpenoid sysnthesis in Centella asiatica cells by methyl-jasmonate
